### Contact Details

thkighie1224@postech.ac.kr

### Version

v5.8.4-stable

### Description

Hello wolfSSL team,

I would like to report an RFC-related bug in which an invalid extension is accepted in a ServerHello message during a TLS 1.2 handshake.

The **Pre-Shared Key Exchange Modes** extension is defined for use in TLS 1.3 handshakes and is only allowed in the ClientHello message. It must not appear in ServerHello, and it must not be processed in TLS 1.2.

However, in wolfSSL, the `TLSX_Parse` function does not reject this extension when it is received in a ServerHello message under TLS 1.2.

Relevant code from `TLSX_Parse`:

```c
case TLSX_PSK_KEY_EXCHANGE_MODES:
    WOLFSSL_MSG("PSK Key Exchange Modes extension received");
#ifdef WOLFSSL_DEBUG_TLS
    WOLFSSL_BUFFER(input + offset, size);
#endif

    if (!IsAtLeastTLSv1_3(ssl->version))
        break;

    if (msgType != client_hello) {
        WOLFSSL_ERROR_VERBOSE(EXT_NOT_ALLOWED);
        return EXT_NOT_ALLOWED;
    }

    ret = PKM_PARSE(ssl, input + offset, size, msgType);
    break;
```

When the negotiated protocol version is TLS 1.2, the IsAtLeastTLSv1_3 check causes execution to hit the break statement. As a result, the extension is silently ignored and no EXT_NOT_ALLOWED error is returned, even if the extension appears in a ServerHello message.

