## Bug Description

In `check_trust()` in `crypto/x509/x509_vfy.c` (line 880), the return value of `sk_X509_set()` is explicitly discarded when replacing the leaf certificate in the chain with a trusted match from the trust store:

```c
// Line 879-882
/* Replace leaf with trusted match */
(void)sk_X509_set(ctx->chain, 0, mx);
X509_free(x);
ctx->num_untrusted = 0;
goto trusted;
```

`sk_X509_set()` returns `NULL` on failure (e.g., if the index is out of bounds). If it fails, the old leaf `x` is freed on line 881 but was never replaced in the chain — leaving `ctx->chain[0]` as a dangling pointer. The function then proceeds to `goto trusted`, and subsequent verification stages operate on a chain with a freed certificate at position 0.

### Why this matters

While `index == 0` on a non-empty chain should always be valid (making this currently safe in practice), the explicit `(void)` cast suppresses any future compiler or static-analysis warning. If the function were ever refactored such that the chain could be empty at this point, or if the index computation changed, this would become a use-after-free with no diagnostic.

The defensive fix is trivial: check the return value before freeing `x`.

### Suggested Fix

```c
/* Replace leaf with trusted match */
if (sk_X509_set(ctx->chain, 0, mx) == NULL) {
    X509_free(mx);
    return -1;
}
X509_free(x);
ctx->num_untrusted = 0;
goto trusted;
```

