A double-free in `crypto/hashtable/hashtable.c::free_oldmd` fires during cleanup of any `X509_STORE`. On `master`/`4.0.0` the bug is reached directly from `X509_STORE_free` (the September 2025 hashtable refactor stores `objs_ht` in the X509_STORE). On `3.6.2` the same `free_oldmd` is reached during `OPENSSL_cleanup` via the default libctx's namemap teardown — so any process that calls `X509_STORE_new` and later runs `OPENSSL_cleanup` (explicitly OR via libcrypto's automatic atexit) hits it.

The 4.0.0 surface is loud: glibc aborts the process with `double free or corruption (!prev)`. The 3.6.2 surface is silent under simple test programs (freed chunks fall back into tcache cleanly); the double-free is real, just not flagged unless heap pressure or an external allocation tracker is present.

