I found an out-of-bounds read in the OpenSSL-encrypted PEM private-key import path in lib/x509/.

The issue is in `gnutls_x509_privkey_import_openssl()` in `lib/x509/privkey_openssl.c`:

- After finding `"DEK-Info: "`, the code computes `pem_header_size` relative to that point (`lib/x509/privkey_openssl.c:170-171`).
- It then advances `pem_header` past the cipher name (`:178`), the hex IV (`:211`), and any trailing newlines (`:217-218`).
- `pem_header_size` is not reduced to match those pointer advances.
- The stale length is then passed to `_gnutls_base64_decode()` (`lib/x509/privkey_openssl.c:220-221`).

In `_gnutls_base64_decode()`, `cpydata()` iterates up to the supplied `data_size` and reads `data[i]` on each iteration (`lib/x509_b64.c:223-229`).

So if the PEM is truncated after the encrypted payload, the stale `pem_header_size` lets the base64 helper continue reading past the end of the caller buffer.

