There is an out-of-bounds read in the Certificate Transparency SCT extension parser in `lib/x509/x509_ext.c`.

The issue is in `gnutls_x509_ext_ct_import_scts()`. After decoding the SCT extension OCTET STRING, the code reads the 2-byte SCT list length and validates it against the full decoded buffer size, instead of the remaining bytes after the length field. This allows a malformed extension to overstate the available SCT list data by up to 2 bytes. The parser can then advance `ptr` beyond the end of the decoded SCT buffer and call `_gnutls_parse_ct_sct()` on an out-of-bounds pointer.

Relevant code:

```c
length = _gnutls_read_uint16(scts_content.data);
if (length < 4 || length > scts_content.size) {
    gnutls_assert();
    ret = GNUTLS_E_REQUESTED_DATA_NOT_AVAILABLE;
    goto cleanup;
}
ptr = &scts_content.data[2];
```

```c
sct_length = _gnutls_read_uint16(ptr);
ptr += 2;
length -= 2;

if (length < sct_length) {
    gnutls_assert();
    ret = GNUTLS_E_REQUESTED_DATA_NOT_AVAILABLE;
    goto cleanup;
}

ret = _gnutls_parse_ct_sct(ptr, sct_length, &sct);
```

```c
sct->version = (int)*ptr;
```

In other words, `length` is checked against `scts_content.size`, but after consuming the 2-byte list-length field only `scts_content.size - 2` bytes remain. Because of that mismatch, the caller can pass an invalid pointer into `_gnutls_parse_ct_sct()`, which immediately dereferences it.

